er","header":"Sailed to Japan at 37","body":"In March 1873, thirty-seven-year-old Eliza Talcott arrived in Kobe, Japan, considered \"relatively old by missionary standards.\" Within two years she had co-founded Kobe Girls' School with Julia Dudley, which became Kobe College in 1894. It remains open today, one hundred and fifty years later."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Known in Japan as \"Eliza Tarukatto\"","body":"Talcott was dubbed the \"Florence Nightingale of Japan\" for her nursing work during the First Sino-Japanese War in Hiroshima in 1894. She learned Japanese quickly and was known in Japan by her transliterated name, Eliza Tarukatto. She died in Kobe on November 1, 1911, having spent nearly four decades in Japan."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Both parents died before she was eighteen","body":"Ralph Talcott died in 1847 when Eliza was eleven; her mother Susan died in 1854 when she was eighteen. Orphaned, she was educated at the Sarah Porter School in Farmington, then returned to teach there before choosing a life of missionary service."}],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — Eliza Talcott","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliza_Talcott"},{"label":"Kobe College Foundation page","url":"https://www.kobe-c.ac.jp/foundation/en/"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"I01220","display_label":"Funded Doshisha; fellow ABCFM Japan mission benefactor","link_text":"Jonathan Newton Harris"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD2818","display_label":"an ABCFM missionary to Angola as Talcott was to Japan"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Eliza","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"nickname":"Eliza Tarukatto","display_name":"Eliza Talcott","photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2f/Eliza_Talcott_003.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Wikimedia Commons."},"military_service":[